Looking through a16z’s "Big Ideas in Tech for 2025" provides a vital sanity check as we plan our long-term engineering roadmaps. By this point, the initial wave of AI hype has started to crystallize into distinct, pragmatic infrastructure layers, and the forecasts reflect this maturation. As an engineer, I see this as a call to move beyond simple API integrations and start thinking about deeper structural shifts—such as how agentic workflows, complex local computation, and new data privacy paradigms are reshaping the basic expectations of enterprise software and consumer applications alike.

For our startup, the challenge is choosing which of these massive structural waves to ride and which to actively ignore. We don't have the resources of a big tech company to experiment in every direction, so we have to be incredibly disciplined in our focus. These partner forecasts help me evaluate where real capital and talent are flowing, offering a map of where the industry is heading. It’s a helpful reminder that building a sustainable business requires us to align our unique product insights with the macroeconomic shifts that will dominate the coming years.

### What stuck with me
* **Pragmatic infrastructure focus**: The industry is moving past early exploratory hype and focusing heavily on building highly robust, production-grade tools.
* **Agentic workflow shifts**: Traditional static user interfaces are being replaced by dynamic, agentic interactions that handle complex tasks autonomously.
* **Ruthless prioritisation strategy**: Small teams must carefully select which technological waves to adopt to avoid diluting their limited resources.
